I think we don't expect 'x' to be definitely assigned in the below program.

Essentially, if the type shape at runtime, doesn't match our expectations, we need to defend against a possibility that none of the switch sections will run.

Switch expressions deal with this by throwing SwitchExpressionException. I think switch statements need to handle it by tracking that the "invisible default label" is reachable here.

```cs
public closed class C;
public class D1 : C;
public class D2 : C;

class Program
{
    public void M(C c)
    {
        int x;
        switch (c)
        {
            case D1:
                x = 1;
                break;
            case D2:
                x = 2;
                break;
            case null:
                x = 3;
                break;
        }
        x.ToString();
    }
}
```
